%N A382610 Area of the unique primitive Pythagorean triple whose inradius is A000045(n) and such that its long leg and its hypotenuse are consecutive natural numbers.
%D A382610 Miguel Ángel Pérez García-Ortega, José Manuel Sánchez Muñoz and José Miguel Blanco Casado, El Libro de las Ternas Pitagóricas, Preprint 2025.
%H A382610 Andrew Howroyd, <a href="/A382610/b382610.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..1000</a>
%H A382610 <a href="/index/Rec#order_09">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (6,-2,-29,16,40,-11,-14,2,1).
%F A382610 a(n) = (A382608(n,1) * A382608(n,2))/2.
%F A382610 a(n) = Fibonacci(n)*(Fibonacci(n) + 1)*(2*Fibonacci(n) + 1).
%F A382610 G.f.: 6*x*(1 - x)*(1 - 4*x - 3*x^2 + 12*x^3 + 6*x^4 - 3*x^5 - x^6)/((1 + x)*(1 - 3*x + x^2)*(1 + x - x^2)*(1 - x - x^2)*(1 - 4*x - x^2)). - _Andrew Howroyd_, Nov 13 2025
%e A382610 For n=2, the short leg is A382608(2,1) = 3 and the long leg is A382608(2,2) = 4 so the area is then a(2) = (3 * 4 )/2 = 6.
%t A382610 a=Table[Fibonacci[n],{n,0,28}];Apply[Join,Map[{#(#+1)(2#+1)}&,a]]
